# Verifier Crash-Safety (Doc-06)

`tests/test.sh` is the harness's only contract with the grader. On every exit path — happy path, early guard, dependency-install failure, pytest collection crash, SIGTERM at the `[verifier].timeout_sec` boundary — Harbor must be able to read `/logs/verifier/reward.txt` and `/logs/verifier/ctrf.json`. If either file is missing, the platform synthesises a "verifier did not run" row that bypasses the real grading signal. The Doc-06 reviewer criterion is the highest-severity rejection cause and gets graded against the static `tests/test.sh` text, not against runtime stats — adding Harbor-level `--retries` does not fix it.

## The five paths that leave reward / ctrf unwritten

Any of these in `tests/test.sh` is enough to fail Doc-06:

1. `exit 1` on a `[ "$PWD" = "/" ]` WORKDIR guard placed **before** the `mkdir -p /logs/verifier && echo 0 > reward.txt` line.
2. `mkdir -p /logs/verifier` failing (read-only filesystem, parent dir missing) — subsequent `echo 0 > …` silently fails too.
3. `uvx`, `pytest`, or `pytest-json-ctrf` failing to initialise (uv not on PATH, transient PyPI failure, syntax error in `test_outputs.py`). `reward.txt` may be `0` from an eager write, but `ctrf.json` was never produced — pytest never reached the `--ctrf` writer.
4. `sha256sum -c -` mismatch on the uv installer (or any other integrity step) with no `|| exit 1` and no `set -e` — script continues to `sh /tmp/uv-install.sh` and runs unverified, OR exits later with no reward write.
5. `[verifier].timeout_sec` SIGKILL hitting the script mid-pytest — `reward.txt` partial write, `ctrf.json` empty or missing.

Pair this rule with `tb2-anti-cheat-completeness.mdc §4` (sha256 hard-gate) — that section is necessary but not sufficient on its own. Adding `|| exit 1` to a script with no trap *creates new unwritten-reward paths*, so the two patterns must ship together.

## The fix: eager writes + `trap ensure_files EXIT`

The skeleton is the same regardless of base image. Two variants differ only in how `uv` gets onto `PATH`.

### Variant A: verbatim V2 (Python-slim or any Dockerfile without `curl` pre-installed)

Use when the Dockerfile is `python:3.13-slim`, `debian:bookworm-slim` without `curl` in the apt install list, or anything similar. `apt-get install -y curl` plus `curl … install.sh | sh` run at verifier time.

```bash
#!/bin/bash
set -e

mkdir -p /logs/verifier
echo 0 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
echo '{"version":"1.0.0","results":{"tool":{"name":"pytest"},"summary":{"tests":0,"passed":0,"failed":0,"skipped":0},"tests":[]}}' > /logs/verifier/ctrf.json

ensure_files() {
    if [ ! -f /logs/verifier/ctrf.json ]; then
        echo '{"version":"1.0.0","results":{"tool":{"name":"pytest"},"summary":{"tests":0,"passed":0,"failed":0,"skipped":0},"tests":[]}}' > /logs/verifier/ctrf.json
    fi
    if [ ! -f /logs/verifier/reward.txt ]; then
        echo 0 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
    fi
}
trap ensure_files EXIT

if [ "$PWD" = "/" ]; then
    echo "Error: No working directory set. Please set a WORKDIR in your Dockerfile."
    exit 1
fi

apt-get update -qq
apt-get install -y -qq curl

curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/0.9.5/install.sh | sh

source $HOME/.local/bin/env

set +e
uvx \
  -p 3.13 \
  -w pytest==8.4.1 \
  -w pytest-json-ctrf==0.3.5 \
  pytest --ctrf /logs/verifier/ctrf.json /tests/test_outputs.py -rA

if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
  echo 1 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
else
  echo 0 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
fi
```

### Variant B: smart graft (Dockerfile with `curl` already in the image)

Use when the Dockerfile is `debian:bookworm-slim` (or similar) with `curl` in the apt install list. Skips runtime apt, conditional-installs uv only when missing, and verifies the installer SHA-256 against `UV_INSTALL_SHA256=8402ab80d2ef…` (the value already pinned in image-build Dockerfiles).

```bash
#!/bin/bash
# Test-only dependencies are bootstrapped here at test time (uv + pytest) so
# the image build itself stays free of test deps. The uv installer URL and
# its body are sha256-pinned for reproducibility.

set -e

mkdir -p /logs/verifier
echo 0 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
echo '{"version":"1.0.0","results":{"tool":{"name":"pytest"},"summary":{"tests":0,"passed":0,"failed":0,"skipped":0},"tests":[]}}' > /logs/verifier/ctrf.json

ensure_files() {
    if [ ! -f /logs/verifier/ctrf.json ]; then
        echo '{"version":"1.0.0","results":{"tool":{"name":"pytest"},"summary":{"tests":0,"passed":0,"failed":0,"skipped":0},"tests":[]}}' > /logs/verifier/ctrf.json
    fi
    if [ ! -f /logs/verifier/reward.txt ]; then
        echo 0 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
    fi
}
trap ensure_files EXIT

export PATH="/root/.local/bin:/usr/local/bin:$PATH"

if [ "$PWD" = "/" ]; then
    echo "Error: No working directory set. Please set a WORKDIR in your Dockerfile before running this script."
    exit 1
fi

if ! command -v uv >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    UV_INSTALL_SHA256="8402ab80d2ef54d7044a71ea4e4e1e8db3b20c87c7bffbc30bff59f1e80ebbd5"
    curl -LsSf --retry 5 --retry-delay 3 --retry-connrefused \
        https://astral.sh/uv/0.9.5/install.sh -o /tmp/uv-install.sh
    echo "${UV_INSTALL_SHA256}  /tmp/uv-install.sh" | sha256sum -c - || exit 1
    sh /tmp/uv-install.sh
    rm -f /tmp/uv-install.sh
fi

set +e
uvx \
  -p 3.13 \
  -w pytest==8.4.1 \
  -w pytest-json-ctrf==0.3.5 \
  pytest --ctrf /logs/verifier/ctrf.json /tests/test_outputs.py -rA

if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
  echo 1 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
else
  echo 0 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
fi
```

## Variant C (Dockerfile-baked `curl` + `uv`)

Some Edition-2 maintainer checklists now require **`curl` and `uv` to be installed in `environment/Dockerfile`** during image build, with a **slim `tests/test.sh`** that only runs `uvx … pytest` (plus the Doc-06 eager `reward.txt` / `ctrf.json` writes, `trap ensure_files EXIT`, `WORKDIR` guard, and `set +e` before pytest — identical spine to Variant A after dependencies exist).

Typical Dockerfile additions:

```dockerfile
RUN apt-get update -qq \
    && apt-get install -y -qq --no-install-recommends ca-certificates curl \
    && curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/0.9.5/install.sh | sh \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
ENV PATH="/root/.local/bin:${PATH}"
```

`tests/test.sh` **must not** repeat `apt-get install curl` or pipe the uv installer when Variant C is in force — duplicate bootstrap is a reviewer warning and adds verifier-time failure modes.

## Variant selection

**Unless Variant C is required for the task**, default to **Variant A** everywhere. Reviewers have consistently pushed back on Variant B submissions even when Variant B is technically more robust (SHA-pin + retry + conditional install). The empirical pattern across `cpp-arp-neighbor-cache-replay-medium`, `cpp-tail-sampling-trace-replay-medium`, `cpp-singleflight-coalesce-replay-medium`, and `cpp-lease-fencing-replay-medium` is that the canonical sample `test.sh` shape is Variant A, and any divergence (header comments, `export PATH=...`, SHA-pin block, retry flags) gets flagged as nonconforming to the reviewer's reference.

The historical corollary was that **`environment/Dockerfile` should NOT bake `curl` in** — let `test.sh` install `curl` at verifier time via `apt-get install -y -qq curl`. **When Variant C applies**, install `curl` and `uv` in the Dockerfile instead and keep `test.sh` to `uvx` only. Otherwise keep only true compile/link deps in the Dockerfile (`ca-certificates`, `g++`, `make`, `nlohmann-json3-dev`, `libssl-dev` if the agent's binary actually links against OpenSSL) and use Variant A for verifier bootstrap.

| Dockerfile signal | Variant | Co-edit |
|---|---|---|
| `python:3.13-slim` or any base without `curl` in `apt-get install` | **A (verbatim V2)** | none |
| `debian:bookworm-slim` + `curl` in `apt-get install` line | **A (verbatim V2)** | **drop `curl` from the Dockerfile** |
| Base image pre-installs `uv` itself (very rare; `gcc:13.x` + explicit `uv` install) | **B (smart graft)** | only acceptable case for Variant B |
| Portal checklist / maintainer guidance: `curl` + uv installer run in Dockerfile; `test.sh` has no `apt-get` / no uv `curl` line | **C (Dockerfile deps)** | slim `test.sh`; same Doc-06 spine as A |

Don't mix A/B/C bootstrap paths (e.g. Dockerfile installs uv **and** `test.sh` curls the installer). Variant A re-installs `uv` every verifier run (the cost is one extra network call); Variant B uses what the image already provides; Variant C pays the network cost once at build time.

### Trade-off you must articulate when proposing Variant A → B hardening

If you find yourself wanting to upgrade a Variant A `test.sh` to Variant B because of a 1-in-10 transient curl/apt flake, stop and check whether the reviewer for the parent task series has already rejected Variant B elsewhere. If yes (it has across the C++ replay series), the right move is to **leave Variant A in place and absorb the flake at the harness retry layer** rather than reland Variant B and trigger another round of review pushback. Document the flake observation in the PR description but don't ship hardening that the reviewer will revert.

## Five non-obvious rules the pattern encodes

1. **Eager writes go BEFORE the WORKDIR guard.** If `[ "$PWD" = "/" ]` `exit 1` fires, the trap still runs because it was installed earlier — but the eager writes already placed valid files. The trap is belt-and-suspenders, not the primary safety net.
2. **`set -e` at the top, `set +e` immediately before pytest.** pytest's non-zero exit is the normal "tests failed" path and must drop to the explicit `if [ $? -eq 0 ]` check. Without `set +e`, the script aborts on pytest failure and the reward stays at `0` only because of the eager write — fragile.
3. **`|| exit 1` on every integrity check** (sha256sum, b2sum, gpg verify). Even with `set -e`, `sha256sum -c -` pipes through `echo`; the pipeline exit code can be masked if `pipefail` isn't set. Inline `|| exit 1` is more grep-able and survives subshells.
4. **The `ensure_files` body checks `[ ! -f … ]`, not file emptiness.** A partial write from a SIGKILL still counts as present; Harbor will parse it. If the partial write produces an invalid CTRF JSON, that's a separate (acceptable) failure mode — better than the synthetic "verifier did not run" row.
5. **`source $HOME/.local/bin/env`** (Variant A) assumes `$HOME` resolves to `/root` under Harbor's exec context. Variant B's `export PATH=…` is more robust when `$HOME` is stripped.

## Pre-submit grep checks

Run from the task root:

```bash
# 1. Both eager writes present at the top of test.sh
rg -n "echo 0 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt" tests/test.sh \
  || echo "WARN: eager reward.txt write missing"
rg -n '"version":"1.0.0"' tests/test.sh \
  || echo "WARN: skeleton ctrf.json write missing"

# 2. Trap installed
rg -n "trap ensure_files EXIT" tests/test.sh \
  || echo "WARN: ensure_files trap missing - script is not crash-safe"

# 3. WORKDIR guard not before the eager writes
grep -n 'PWD' tests/test.sh | head -1 \
  | awk -F: '{ pwd_line=$1 }
             END {
               getline mkdir_line < "/dev/stdin"
             }' \
  # simpler: visually verify mkdir line < PWD line in `cat -n tests/test.sh`

# 4. set -e at top, set +e before uvx
rg -n "^set -e$" tests/test.sh | head -1 \
  || echo "WARN: set -e missing at top"
rg -n "^set \+e$" tests/test.sh | head -1 \
  || echo "WARN: set +e before pytest missing (script will abort on pytest failure)"

# 5. sha256sum has hard gate (only if Variant B with sha-verify)
rg -n "sha256sum -c" tests/test.sh \
  | rg -v "\|\| exit" \
  && echo "WARN: sha256sum without || exit 1 (silent-pass risk)"

# 6. Pick one bootstrap surface: Variant C (Dockerfile uv) XOR A/B (test.sh curl)
if rg -q "curl -LsSf" environment/Dockerfile && rg -q "curl -LsSf" tests/test.sh; then
  echo "WARN: uv installer appears in both Dockerfile and test.sh — use Variant C (image only) or A/B (test.sh), not both"
fi
```

Each `WARN:` is a likely reviewer flag.

## Variant decision flowchart

```
Does the portal / maintainer checklist require curl + uv in Dockerfile
with a slim test.sh (no runtime apt / no runtime uv curl)?
├── Yes → Variant C (Dockerfile installs curl + uv; PATH includes
│         ~/.local/bin; test.sh = Doc-06 spine + uvx pytest only)
└── No  → Default: Variant A (canonical sample shape). Drop curl from the
          Dockerfile if it's currently there. Keep only true C++ build deps.

          Is uv pre-installed in the base image (very rare; gcc:13.x with
          explicit RUN curl ... uv install)?
          ├── No  → Variant A (verbatim V2)
          └── Yes → Variant B (smart graft, with `if ! command -v uv` block)
```

The Variant B "skip apt because curl is already in the image" optimisation has been rejected by reviewers across at least four C++ replay tasks. Stop reaching for it on Dockerfiles that have curl baked in — **unless you are deliberately on Variant C**, drop curl from the Dockerfile instead and stay on Variant A.

## Sister rules

- `tb2-anti-cheat-completeness.mdc §4` covers the literal `sha256sum -c - || exit 1` line. This rule covers the broader crash-safety pattern that makes that hard exit safe (otherwise `|| exit 1` itself becomes an unwritten-reward path).
- `tb2-task-rejection-signals.mdc §11` is the master-checklist entry pointing at this rule.
- `tb2-prelaunch-checklist.mdc` Stage 5 includes the crash-safe verifier as part of the manual eyes-on review.

## Origin

Derived from manual reviewer feedback ("the verifier is not crash-safe: it has at least five independent paths where a failure leaves `/logs/verifier/reward.txt` unwritten — Doc-06 first and highest-severity reviewer criterion") and a Harbor `terminus_2 send_keys` flake on `cpp-link-resolution-audit-hard` that surfaced the synthetic "verifier did not run" row.

The two-variant split was originally discovered while normalising `tests/test.sh` across the submission tree: Python-slim image tasks (`sbom-vulnerability-impact-hard`, `limit-order-book-matching-medium`, `ansible-dependency-impact-hard`) needed runtime curl + uv install (Variant A), while C++ debian-bookworm tasks with `curl` in the Dockerfile (`cpp-region-coalescer-replay-medium`, `cpp-circuit-breaker-replay-medium`, `cpp-bgp-best-path-replay-medium`, `cpp-image-layer-dedupe-replay-medium`) could keep their existing supply-chain hardening (SHA-pinned conditional install + retry flags) and just graft the trap on top (Variant B).

The "default to Variant A everywhere; drop curl from Dockerfile" guidance was added after reviewers consistently pushed back on Variant B submissions across `cpp-arp-neighbor-cache-replay-medium`, `cpp-tail-sampling-trace-replay-medium`, `cpp-singleflight-coalesce-replay-medium`, and `cpp-lease-fencing-replay-medium`. The empirical signal is that the canonical sample `test.sh` shape (Variant A) is what reviewers grade against, even though Variant B is technically more robust against network flakes.
